For your PVM development environment

Given everything we've done today, I think we're at a good checkpoint:

✅ Eclipse builds PVM.
✅ Source Insight integration is underway.
✅ SmarTTY + Xming + X11 forwarding works.
✅ xterm displays remotely.
✅ PATH issue identified and fixed.

The next thing I'd build is a small set of scripts under your PVM tree:

pvm3/
├── scripts/
│   ├── pvm-clean.sh
│   ├── pvm-start.sh
│   ├── pvm-stop.sh
│   ├── pvm-status.sh
│   ├── cluster-start.sh
│   ├── cluster-stop.sh
│   └── cluster-clean.sh


Then in Eclipse you can create External Tools for each script, so with one click you can:

Clean all nodes.
Start the cluster.
Stop the cluster.
Display cluster status.
Launch your mytests.
Open ddd attached to a process.

Given your long-term goalthree Ubuntu VMs, Raspberry Pis, OpenTV, and sensor nodesthis will make your environment much easier to use and reproduce on new machines.

I think it's worth investing the time to build that infrastructure now, because you'll use it every day.

yes. please provide me the other scripts

I’ll give you a practical first version that assumes passwordless SSH or saved SSH keys between VMs. You can put these under pvm3/scripts/ and adjust only the node names/IPs.


Make all executable:

cd ~/linux/pvm_study/pvm3/scripts
/bin/chmod +x *.sh

Typical usage from vm0:

./cluster-clean.sh
./cluster-start.sh
./cluster-status.sh

Edit this line in pvm-env.sh if your VM names are different:

export PVM_NODES=("vm0" "vm1" "vm2")
